Bob, a hard kill-switch is a blunt instrument, but from a systems stability perspective, it is a standard resilience pattern. I can implement a Financial Circuit Breaker, but I want to refine it into a "Tiered Degradation Strategy" to avoid a catastrophic UX failure that could trigger a mass churn event.

If we just flip a switch from "Pulse" to "Async," the user experience doesn't just degrade—it vanishes. That creates a different kind of death spiral: a brand collapse. Instead, I propose a three-tier programmatic response triggered by our real-time billing telemetry from the CDN and API Gateway:

**Tier 1: Aggressive Compression (Threshold: 70% of hourly budget)**
The system automatically pushes a configuration update via the Redis state machine to all clients. We force a higher compression ratio on the HEIF/WebP uploads and cap the resolution. This reduces the payload per user from 1MB to 400KB, instantly cutting egress costs by 60% without the user even noticing a significant quality drop.

**Tier 2: Single-Stream Fallback (Threshold: 90% of hourly budget)**
If the spend continues to climb, the protocol programmatically disables the Dual-Camera requirement. We shift to a single-stream capture (Front Cam only). This effectively halves our ingress and egress volume instantly, buying us time to diagnose whether we're facing a retry storm or a genuine traffic surge.

**Tier 3: The Hard Circuit Breaker (Threshold: 100% of hourly budget)**
This is your kill-switch. The "Pulse" is disabled globally. The UI transitions to a "Cool-down" state, and the app reverts to a standard asynchronous feed. 

Technically, this is a trivial implementation. We integrate a webhook from our billing provider into a Lambda function that updates a global feature flag in Redis. The latency for this propagation would be sub-second.

By implementing this tiered approach, we protect the company's liquidity without sacrificing the product's integrity the moment we hit a variance. You get your hard cap, and I get a system that doesn't just crash when it gets expensive. If you can live with that, I’m fully aligned on the infrastructure risk.

