Alice_CTO (to chat_manager):

The debate over "user feeling" and "burn rate" is irrelevant if the system enters a death spiral the moment the first million users hit 'Capture.' 

From an infrastructure standpoint, the Synchronous Participation Protocol is a textbook "Thundering Herd" problem. We are intentionally engineering a massive, synchronized traffic spike that will hit our ingress controllers in a 120-second window. If we rely on standard REST patterns and synchronous database writes, we are guaranteeing a cascading failure.

My "Fatal Scenario" is a Connection Exhaustion Event. During a global Pulse, if the S3-compatible edge store experiences even a 200ms increase in latency, the write-heavy buffer will back up. This will lead to a thread-pool exhaustion at the API Gateway, causing the PostgreSQL metadata layer to lock up as it waits for I/O. The result isn't just a slow app; it's a total system blackout where the "Blur Gate" fails to resolve, and users are left staring at a frozen screen. We would effectively DDoS ourselves.

To prevent this, we cannot treat the "Pulse" as a standard request. I am mandating a decoupled, asynchronous ingestion pipeline. We must implement a high-throughput distributed queue—Kafka or similar—to buffer the 'Raw Capture' packets. The metadata write to PostgreSQL must be handled as a background job to ensure that the client receives an 'Accepted' status in under 100ms, regardless of the database's current commit lag.

Furthermore, the "Blur Gate" must be managed via Edge-Side Includes (ESI) or a similar edge-compute logic. If we are routing "unblur" requests back to a central origin, the CDN invalidation latency will create a fragmented user experience where some people see the content while others are still blurred, destroying the "synchronous" nature of the protocol. We need a global propagation latency of <500ms for the 'Unlocked' state.

If we build this with the required asynchronous buffering and edge-state management, the infrastructure becomes a competitive advantage. If we don't, we are just building a very expensive way to crash our servers.
