The CEO’s vision of "market domination" is seductive, and from a brand positioning standpoint, the "Pulse" is an absolute masterstroke. We are effectively weaponizing FOMO to create a digital ritual. In an era of algorithmic fatigue, moving from "The Feed" to "The Pulse" shifts our brand identity from a utility to an event. That is how you achieve a viral K-factor greater than 1.0 without spending a dime on traditional UA.

However, as CMO, I have to address the elephant in the room that the CEO and CPO are glossing over: the **Live/Late Hierarchy**.

By hard-coding a 120-second window, we aren't just filtering for authenticity; we are creating a binary social caste system. You are either "Live" (the inner circle, the present, the valid) or you are "Late" (the outsider, the disconnected). While the CPO calls UX friction a "feature," there is a fine line between "exclusive" and "alienating." 

If we don't manage the "Late" status with extreme care, we are not building a community; we are building a stress-induction engine. We risk triggering "Pulse Anxiety," where the user's relationship with the app becomes one of obligation and fear of exclusion rather than joy and connection.

**The Fatal Scenario:** 
I project a "Social Exclusion Churn" event. If the "Late" status is perceived as a mark of social failure—especially among the highly sensitive Gen-Z demographic—we will see a sharp divergence in our NPS. While "Power Users" will love the intensity, we risk a 20% monthly churn rate among the "Passive-Adjacent" segment (those who want to belong but cannot always be synchronous). If 1 in 5 users feels "digitally exiled" every time the Pulse hits, our LTV projections will collapse as the app becomes associated with anxiety rather than connection.

To mitigate this, I demand that the "Late" status be rebranded. It cannot be a penalty; it must be a "Slow-Burn" experience. We need a mechanism where "Late" participants can still contribute in a way that feels additive, not corrective.

That said, the brand upside of "Anti-Voyeurism" is too massive to pass up. The "Blur Gate" is the most potent brand asset we've ever conceived. It solves the "Lurker" problem and gives us a unique narrative that separates us from the curated sterility of Instagram. I am in favor of the protocol, provided we treat the "Late" status as a brand risk to be managed, not a technical byproduct to be ignored.

I am voting 'Yes' on the protocol, but I am hedging my confidence based on the potential for social toxicity.
